<br />

<br />
Matrix has levels.  But it doesn't have real "loot".   You use information to buy weapons and cloths, sure, but more importantly you use it to increase your skills and buy new skills.  See, your skills don't increase automatically when you level, and you are never limited in what you can become.  When I played I decided that I wanted to be every type of Hacker available (at that point, it meant generally a healer, a debuffer, and an AEer), every kind of Operative available (again, at that point it meant the ability to fight with guns - including machine guns, handguns, rifles - the "spy"-type abilities, and the hand-to-hand type abilities) and every kind of coder available (basically, think of coders as guys who can make pets or creations within the Matrix).  Although you are limited by how much memory you have in your head, you CAN do all those things.  Essentially I'd log in one day and decide I wanted to kick karate butt and I'd load up the skills to do that.  The next day I might want to fling spells at people, the next I might want to join my friends as a healer.  It was extremely fluid.  I'm not sure how the game has progressed, but I definitely appreciated that it wasn't necessarily linear.  Leveling does bring additional skill trees and power as well as additional memory in which to memorize more skills, but you were never set in what you had to do any day of the week. 
<br />

<br />
FYI, the great thing about Matrix right now is if you pre-order you get an auto Beta invite.  I also understand that you can also CANCEL your pre-order after receiving your beta invite.  Also, if one had access to the client download many people like me have unused beta accounts lying around. 
<br />

<br />

<br />
In terms of fantasy games, I haven't seen anything that really takes a new path...so I've just picked my favorite (WoW) and will stick with that.  I'm not going to try and talk you into it, but I will note that just because a world is the stereotypical "fantasy world" does not mean the game interaction is the same.  Some people really don't like the game for legitimate reasons, but in my opinion there is a justifiable reason for the "fanboi" flavor you often see in writings about it.  Maybe something reallyreally "new" will come out - hasn't happened so far.  I keep hoping for a virtual reality game a la Tad Williams or Dennis R. McKiernan but alas I'm going to be disappointed for decades to come.</span><span class="postbody"><br />_________________<br /><img src="http://www.therambler.net/images/sigs/devon2.jpg" border="0" /></span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
                        </tr>
                </table></td>
        </tr>
	<tr>
