                        <tr>
                                <td colspan="2"><span class="postbody">I'd kill for a system of advancement based on the player getting better at playing instead of just getting more hp and whatnot. The most common means of getting that is pvp, like the aforementioned fps (innit there a mmo fps? planetside or somesuch?). As long as people can be counted on to have reasonably similair gear and there is some goal other than getting gear (taking enemy capitol, etc), it could work. Alternatively, games like Wish could try it by making leveling optional, but it seems like that game will still have stat advancement and probably won't support the kind of player skill that you get from a common fps (or from playing an enchanter in EQ1). 
<br />

<br />
I've got my eye on WoW but am currently playing EQ2 for the "this game is tough" part (under the assumption that once I finish the level treadmill, like in Eq1, i can jump into the big game hunting I so dearly love). Since you like neither, I don't really know any others to recommend, but I'd sure like to know if I've got a third (or fourth, counting Wish) choice.</span><span class="postbody"></span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
